We recommended the following:
 The Municipal Engineer and the Municipal General Services Officer conduct a yearly physical inventory of local road network projects and accordingly update the local road map of the MLGU; 
 The General Services Officer (Municipal Treasurer) to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; 
 The Municipal Accountant to trace the recorded road, highways and bridges which were closed to government equity prior to 2016 and subsequently record in its books of accounts the amount of road works equivalent to the required transition provision, and keep and maintain Registry of Public Infrastructures for Roads and subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and provide for the depreciation for the local road network; and 
 The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

We recommended that management:
 demand from the Municipal Treasurer the return or refund of the amount unliquidated since the purposes of her cash advances has been served; 
 submit the original acknowledgement receipt for the honoraria of barangay health workers totaling ₱28,800.00; 
 henceforth, ensure that no additional cash advances are allowed to any official unless the previous cash advance is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made; 
 ensure that the specific purpose of the grant is specified in the disbursement voucher and the amount granted is equal to the net amount of the payroll or approved estimate for the specific purpose; 
 enforce the full liquidation of all cash advances after the purpose had been served and demand the immediate refund of the excess cash advance upon submission of the Liquidation; and 
 avoid payment of goods through cash advances when direct payment is possible to prevent losses and provide reasonable assurance that the transaction is regular.

6.8 We recommended the following:
6.8.1 the Municipal Accountant –
6.8.1.1 record the proposed adjustments under paragraph 6.4 to
correct the errors on recording current year’s transactions;
6.8.1.2 trace the unaccounted difference of ₱55,558.87 and
₱41,613.76 for GF and SEF, respectively from Nov. 2018
balance and record adjustments accordingly;
6.8.1.3 observe due diligence on recording collections and deposits;
6.8.2 the Municipal Treasurer –
6.8.2.1 deposit all collections promptly and intact with the
authorized government bank, in pursuant to COA and
Ministry of Finance JC No. 1-81;
6.8.2.2 observe due diligence on recording collections and deposits;
6.8.3 the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer –
6.8.3.1 Reconcile monthly the accounting with the treasury records
pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002 to immediately
detect errors and adjust their records accordingly;
6.8.3.2 Trace back the ₱5,000.00 balance under the Trust Fund to account
for the un-reconciled discrepancy.

6.6	We have recommended the following:
That cash advances be granted, utilized and liquidated in accordance with COA Circular No. 97-002. For this, make sure that cash advances are granted only to authorized officers, properly utilized and liquidated accordingly;
That management strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation reports and supporting documents;
That the Municipal Accountant send final demand letters to those former employees with outstanding cash advances requesting for the liquidation or refund of cash advances granted to them; and
That the disbursement vouchers pertaining to the grant of cash advances and copies of demand letters be submitted to the Auditor for proper action. For the cash advances where the person liable is already deceased, management may request for authority to write off the amount in accordance with the provisions of COA Memorandum No. 2002-053 and Rule VI of the 2009 Revised Rules of Procedure of the Commission on Audit.

11.4	In view of the above noted lapses, we have recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant prepare an adjusting entry for errors committed which understated the Due to GSIS account by ₱124,277.08;
The Municipal Treasurer to immediately remit the unpaid premiums/ contributions to GSIS totaling ₱68,790.35, as well as the Due to PhilHealth account amounting to ₱14,429.02.

28.6	In view of the foregoing observations, we have recommended that management:
Justify the noted deficiencies;
Require the MDRRMO-Designate to prepare and submit to the audit team the report of utilization of the LDRRMF. Henceforth, utilization reports should be submitted on the prescribed time set forth by COA Circular No. 2012-002;
Include in the LDRRMFIP the programs, projects and activities to be funded by the unexpended LDRRMF from previous years;
See to it that unexpended/unobligated funds from prior years LDRRM are treated as Trust Liability; and
Henceforth, provide in the Notes to Financial Statements all the required disclosures as mandated under COA Circular No. 2014-002.

31.9	In view of the noted lapses, we have recommended the following:
The Municipal Mayor creates a GFPS Execom, TWG and Secretariat that will supervise, advocate and install a GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) as well as the required Gender  Responsive Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) System;
The Municipal Mayor with the help of the Sangguniang Bayan, formulate and adapt a Local GAD Code;
The MSWDO being the leading authority in identifying gender related issues and concerns, see to it that GAD activities are identified through the use of HGDG, that the GAD plan are regularly updated and that the identified projects do address the GAD issues and concern in the long run; and
Henceforth, management should follow the prescribed format of GAD plan and see to it that said plan and budget are approved by the DILG and the PPDO.

We have recommended: 

That management identify priority projects to be funded under the 20% development fund with sufficient details and particulars. Guidelines and policies involving the implementation of these programs or projects should be considered and included in the planning and budgeting stage;
That management submit the Program of Works as supporting documents to the Annual Investment Plan to aid in the further analysis of funded projects vis-a-vis actual expenditures. For lump sum appropriation, authorization from the Sangguniang Bayan should be obtained before implementation;
That management implement only projects set forth in the Annual Investment Program. In instances where other priority projects are identified for implementation, a Sangguniang Bayan resolution should first be passed for the realignment and revision of the Annual Investment Plan to be submitted for approval by the Sangguniang Panlalawigan;
That management maintain records or registries for all the programs and projects appropriated under the fund including continuing appropriations; and
That management strictly comply with the provisions of DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1 in the preparation and utilization of the 20% Development Fund to attain the desired socio-economic and environmental condition of constituents.

We have recommended that management:

Justify the noted deficiencies;
Allocate thirty percent of the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Fund for the Quick Response Fund to be utilized during disasters and calamities. The 30-70 allocation should be properly specified in the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Plan for proper implementation of projects and monitoring thereof;
Require the MDRRMO-Designate to prepare and submit to the audit team the report of utilization of the LDRRMF. Utilization reports should be submitted on the prescribed time set forth by the COA Circular No. 2012-002;
Provide the liquidation documents for the received in-kind goods and locally procured goods amounting to P 375,000.00;
Utilize the prior years’ trust liability for immediate assistance and services to calamity stricken constituents;
See to it that unexpended/unobligated funds from prior years’ LDRRM are treated as Trust Liability; and
Henceforth, provide in the Notes to Financial Statements all the required disclosures as mandated under COA Circular No. 2014-002.

